<header class="header">
  <h1>Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Calendar days don’t measure heat.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    But even inside that frost-free window, temperature determines how fast crops actually develop.
    “Days to maturity” assumes consistent warmth — and in cold climates, that assumption often breaks down.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Sets the Clock — But Temperature Controls the Speed</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate frames frost dates using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your last spring frost and first fall frost define a typical seasonal boundary — not a guarantee, but a planning anchor.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you haven’t identified your frost window yet, you can start with the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Once frost risk drops below the 32°F threshold in spring, the clock begins.
    Once fall frost risk returns, the clock stops.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the clock doesn’t run at the same speed everywhere.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What “Days to Maturity” Actually Assumes</h2>

  <p>
    When a seed packet says “85 days to maturity,” that number assumes reasonably warm growing conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    It does not mean:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>85 calendar days regardless of temperature</li>
    <li>85 days of cool nights and slow growth</li>
    <li>85 days in a marginal climate</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In warm climates, development speed may match those assumptions.
    In cold climates, development often slows because temperature drives plant metabolism.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Heat Accumulation Drives Development</h2>

  <p>
    Crops progress through growth stages based on accumulated heat — not simply elapsed days.
  </p>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) measure that accumulated heat.
    Most warm-season crops use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − Base Temperature
  </pre>

  <p>
    If your early summer nights remain cool, daily GDD totals are lower.
    Lower daily totals mean slower cumulative development.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how much heat typically accumulates in your location using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Same 85-Day Crop, Different Outcomes</h2>

  <p>
    Imagine two gardeners both planting an 85-day tomato variety after their typical last frost.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Gardener A</strong> accumulates 2,400 GDD before first frost.</li>
    <li><strong>Gardener B</strong> accumulates 1,800 GDD before first frost.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Gardener A may see full ripening well before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gardener B may still have green fruit when 32°F arrives.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar count is the same.
    The heat accumulation is not.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why This Matters in Short Growing Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    In northern climates, higher elevations, and interior continental regions,
    early and late season temperatures are often mild.
  </p>

  <p>
    As explained in
    <a href="/guides/why-frost-dates-matter-more-than-planting-calendars/">Why Frost Dates Matter More Than Planting Calendars</a>,
    calendar-based planting advice ignores climate variability.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even if your frost-free window appears long enough on paper,
    slower heat accumulation can compress effective development time.
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s why short-season gardeners often find that “on-time” planting still produces late harvests.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Tolerance and Maturity Margins</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates are probability-based,
    some years provide more heat than others.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your crop’s expected GDD requirement nearly equals your typical seasonal accumulation,
    your margin for variation is small.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your climate typically accumulates well beyond the crop’s requirement,
    your buffer is larger.
  </p>

  <p>
    The key question shifts from:
  </p>

  <p>
    “How many days does this crop take?”
  </p>

  <p>
    to:
  </p>

  <p>
    “Will I accumulate enough heat before first frost in a typical year?”
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Plan More Accurately</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify your 50% frost dates using the 32°F definition.</li>
    <li>Calculate your frost-free season length.</li>
    <li>Estimate total GDD accumulation inside that window.</li>
    <li>Choose varieties with heat requirements that fit comfortably within that total.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    If you need additional margin, starting seeds earlier indoors may help —
    provided it meaningfully shifts transplant timing relative to frost risk.
    You can anchor indoor timing using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    When frost timing and heat accumulation are evaluated together,
    maturity planning becomes climate-based rather than calendar-based.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>“Days to maturity” assumes warm growing conditions.</li>
    <li>Cool climates accumulate heat more slowly.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure development progress.</li>
    <li>Short growing seasons often require lower heat-demand varieties.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In cold climates, calendar days are not the limiting factor.
    Heat accumulation is.
  </p>
</section>